title: Experimental study of the 19-O(d,p)20-O reaction in inverse kinematics

inverse kinematics

x4freetext: Experiment was carried out using
Argonne Tandem-LINAC Accelerator System at Argonne
National Laboratory
Deuterated polyethylene (CD2) target of thickness 260
mu-g/cm2
Reaction target was placed on axis of a
superconducting solenoid. Emitted light particles are
transported in homogeneous magnetic field back to the
axis, where they are detected. In HELIOS,angle
measurements of light ions in inverse kinematics are
transformed into position measurements along the
solenoid axis. Recoiling ions were detected by target
recoil detector placed downstream of the target.
Protons were detected using Si detector array.
The array measures the energy, return distance, and
flight time of the detected particles.The silicon-
detector array is designed so that particles are
detected close to the solenoid axis to simplify the
time of flight measurement. Each detector is made from
a 12mm x56mm silicon wafer with an active area of
9mm x 50.5mm and a thickness of 700 mu-m.
Recoiling ions were detected 1.3 m
downstream of the target by a recoil detector
consisting of four dE-E Si telescopes with
thicknesses of 80 and 500 mu-m.
Coincidence between protons and
recoil ions was required
The radioactive 19-O beam was produced through the
2H(18-O,19-O)1H reaction using a primary 18-O beam
with an energy of 8.06 MeV/u. The production target
was a cryogenically cooled gas cell which held
deuterium gas at a pressure of 1400 mbar and at a
temperature of 180 deg C. A maximum beam current of
500 enA was put on the gas cell resulting in an 19-O
secondary-beam rate of (2 - 4)E+5 p/s.
Light charged particles were identified by
mass-to-charge ratios through their cyclotron period,
independent of their kinetic energy
